</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>SCR76:v97#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="SCR76"/><meta name="dc:title" content="SCR &#xA;              76-&#xA;                CHAPTERED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div width="100%" style="text-align:center;"><div id="bill_num_title_chap"><span style="text-align:center;font-weight:bold;font-size:1.1em;font-family:'Times New Roman'; "><b>
                Senate Concurrent Resolution
              
                        No. 76</b></span></div><div style="text-align:center;padding-top: 1.0em;padding-bottom: 1.2em;" id="chap_num_title_chap"><span style="font-size:1.4em;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-weight:normal;">
                      CHAPTER 129</span></div></div><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> Relative to food allergy awareness.</span></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center">
                  
                  [<span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Filed with
              </span><span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Secretary of State
              </span> <span style="font-size: 13pt">July 03, 2025.
                      </span>]
                </div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SCR 76, Valladares.
                          Food allergy awareness.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This measure would declare May as Food Allergy Awareness Month and would encourage all Californians to increase their understanding of food allergies, support preventative practices, and learn how to respond in the event of a severe allergic reaction.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><span class="Resolution" title="source: /caml:MeasureDoc/caml:Resolution&#xA;    "><span class="Whereas" id="id_29A1995C-5C68-4238-9648-2B7FDB38DE71"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, An estimated 33 million people in the United States are living with food allergies, a serious and potentially life-threatening medical condition; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_DD5C080E-63FF-4DF2-9526-8A5B64B12BCE"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Research shows that food allergies are increasingly common among children, with an estimated 6 million youth under 18 years of age, approximately 2 students in every classroom, are affected by one or more food allergies; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_FA172D1D-EA06-4982-A5B3-025169A7A208"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The nine most common food allergens, which are shellfish, fish, milk, eggs, tree nuts, peanuts, soy, wheat, and sesame, are responsible for 90 percent of all allergic reactions in the United States; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_66C4C20E-9867-477F-A07B-CE08B9DF8291"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, A food allergy is caused when the immune system mistakenly identifies a harmless food protein, an allergen, as a threat, leading to the release of antibodies that trigger reactions ranging from mild symptoms to severe anaphylaxis; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_3EF99F9B-66E8-4FB0-9FFB-7776E3FDA2EE"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Symptoms of a food allergy may include tingling of the mouth, swelling of the throat, difficulty breathing, hives, vomiting, a dangerous drop in blood pressure, unconsciousness, or death; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_07087464-365C-4943-99ED-DD1DC3E23DE5"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, According to the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, at least two in five children, or 40 percent, have been treated in the emergency department for a food allergy reaction; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_02183BFE-9739-41D2-A6F1-564F456A88AC"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Anaphylaxis is a severe, rapid-onset allergic reaction that can impact multiple systems in the body within minutes of exposure and may be fatal without immediate intervention; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_0EB4851E-B327-4E61-B81C-BDC5C0C33573"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, There is no cure for food allergies, the only treatment for anaphylaxis is epinephrine, and the only proven prevention is complete avoidance of the triggering allergen; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_4C56897A-1694-4D8F-B9C3-558D64BFD0F1"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Education, public awareness, and continued investment in scientific research are critical to improving health outcomes and quality of life for individuals living with food allergies; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_4C9055DC-3ED6-4115-BE46-6C1709044058"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Zacky Muñoz, a student from California, has become a leading national voice in food allergy advocacy, using his platform to bring attention to the urgent need for stronger policies that protect children with life-threatening allergies; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_6F9B5D82-9565-4FCB-B74E-C2D40FF46E13"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Through his courage, vision, and relentless pursuit of change, Zacky is helping to shape legislation that prioritizes safety, expands access to life-saving treatment, and paves the way for a more secure future for individuals and families affected by food allergies; now, therefore, be it</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_D0ABB5AB-477B-46E8-A5A5-385042DB9C86"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved by the Senate of the State of California, the Assembly thereof concurring, That the Legislature encourages all Californians to increase their understanding of food allergies, support preventative practices, and learn how to respond in the event of a severe allergic reaction; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_58E1DE98-D4FC-4429-82E6-ECA4172AD835"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That May is Food Allergy Awareness Month; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_A0700A10-895C-4AF4-AD00-82CBBA69CDF9"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Secretary of the Senate transmit copies of this resolution to the author for appropriate distribution.</div></span></span></div></body></html>
